                <h2>Introduction</h2>
<blockquote>
<p>In the field of overseas marketing, Google Ads, as the world's largest search advertising platform, is the core channel for many enterprises to acquire quality traffic. However, issues like account suspension and ad disapprovals have troubled many advertisers. Once an account is restricted, it not only affects advertising schedules but may also lead to data loss and budget waste.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This article systematically analyzes the core techniques for preventing Google Ads account suspension and provides detailed appeal tutorials to help you protect your advertising accounts in the complex environment of 2024.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Part 1: In-Depth Analysis of Common Account Suspension Reasons</h2>
<h3>1.1 Policy Violations and Non-Compliant Content</h3>
<p>Google has strict policies on advertising content. Here are the high-frequency causes of account suspension:</p>
<p><strong>False Advertising</strong>: Exaggerating product efficacy, making false promises, using absolute terms (such as "100% effective" or "guaranteed cure") are all violations. Google's updated healthcare advertising policies in 2023 have stricter requirements for dietary supplements and weight loss products.</p>
<p><strong>Intellectual Property Infringement</strong>: Using brand logos, trademarks, or copyrighted images without authorization, or using well-known brands in ad copy to gain traffic (such as "like Nike" or "cheaper than Apple"), can trigger review mechanisms.</p>
<p><strong>Misleading Content</strong>: Landing page content that doesn't match ad promises, hiding key information (such as additional fees), or using deceptive tactics to induce clicks will be severely punished.</p>
<h3>1.2 Payment-Related Issues</h3>
<p>Payment problems are another major factor causing sudden account suspension:</p>
<p><strong>Credit Card Issues</strong>: Using someone else's credit card, mismatched debit card information with Google account registration, and frequent credit card chargebacks will trigger risk control mechanisms.</p>
<p><strong>Billing Address Mismatch</strong>: Significant differences between credit card billing address and Google account registration address may result in the system flagging abnormal behavior.</p>
<p><strong>Abnormal Budget Fluctuations</strong>: Suddenly increasing budgets in a short period (such as from $100 daily to $10,000) will be marked as suspicious activity.</p>
<h3>1.3 Domain and Landing Page Issues</h3>
<p><strong>Newly Registered Domains</strong>: Advertising with newly registered domains (especially those registered less than 30 days ago) is more likely to trigger reviews.</p>
<p><strong>Low-Quality Landing Pages</strong>: Slow page loading (over 3 seconds), sparse content, numerous dead links, or irrelevant content to ads will result in devaluation or suspension.</p>
<p><strong>Technical Architecture Problems</strong>: Using free hosting services, marked IP addresses, or servers in high-risk regions will affect account security scores.</p>
<h3>1.4 Abnormal Account Operation Behaviors</h3>
<p><strong>Frequent Ad Modifications</strong>: Creating, pausing, or modifying ads in large quantities in a short period will be judged as abnormal operations.</p>
<p><strong>Keyword Violations</strong>: Using Google-prohibited sensitive keywords, trademark words, or competitor keywords as advertising keywords.</p>
<p><strong>Sudden Quality Score Drop</strong>: A sudden significant decline in ad quality score may trigger manual review.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Part 2: Core Strategies for Account Suspension Prevention</h2>
<h3>2.1 Account Structure Optimization</h3>
<p><strong>Proper Account Hierarchy Planning</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Separate management of advertising campaigns for different product lines, regions, and objectives</li>
<li>Control each ad group to 15-20 highly relevant keywords</li>
<li>Set independent budgets and bidding strategies for different advertising campaigns</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example</strong>: A cross-border e-commerce seller selling both 3C accessories and home goods should create two separate advertising campaigns rather than mixing them together.</p>
<h3>2.2 Landing Page Optimization Standards</h3>
<p>High-quality landing pages are the foundation of suspension prevention and must meet the following standards:</p>
<p><strong>Content Completeness</strong>:<br />
- Clear brand information and contact details (phone, email, address)<br />
- Detailed product descriptions and authentic images<br />
- Complete return/exchange policies and privacy policies<br />
- SSL certificate (HTTPS) certification</p>
<p><strong>Technical Specifications</strong>:<br />
- Mobile adaptation (responsive design)<br />
- Page loading speed controlled within 3 seconds<br />
- Clear navigation without dead links and 404 pages<br />
- Regular content updates to avoid becoming a "zombie website"</p>
<h3>2.3 Ad Copy Compliance Review</h3>
<p><strong>Absolute Term Prohibition List</strong>:<br />
- ❌ "Best", "First", "Top", "Champion"<br />
- ❌ "100%", "Guarantee", "Absolutely"<br />
- ❌ "Immediately", "Right Now", "Instantly" (when promising results)</p>
<p><strong>Recommended Replacements</strong>:<br />
- ✅ "High Quality", "Premium", "Trustworthy"<br />
- ✅ "Up to", "May", "Expected"<br />
- ✅ "Register now for limited-time offers"</p>
<h3>2.4 Payment Security Configuration</h3>
<p><strong>Recommended Practices</strong>:<br />
1. Use corporate-level credit or debit cards to ensure billing address matches account registration exactly<br />
2. Prioritize enabling automatic payment mode to avoid投放 delays from manual payments<br />
3. Add multiple payment methods in Payment Settings as backup<br />
4. Regularly check bills to ensure no abnormal charges</p>
<h3>2.5 Domain and Website Security</h3>
<p><strong>Domain Registration Recommendations</strong>:<br />
- Prioritize well-known registrars like GoDaddy and Namecheap<br />
- Recommended registration period is 2+ years to demonstrate long-term operational intent<br />
- Prepare the domain in advance to avoid the high-risk period within 30 days of new registration</p>
<p><strong>Website Security Configuration</strong>:<br />
- Deploy CDN services like Cloudflare to enhance security levels<br />
- Apply for Google Search Console to verify website ownership<br />
- Conduct regular website health checks to ensure no malicious software</p>
<hr />
<h2>Part 3: Detailed Appeal Tutorial</h2>
<h3>3.1 Pre-Appeal Preparation</h3>
<p><strong>Collecting Evidence Materials</strong>:<br />
- Account ID and advertising campaign ID<br />
- Specific ad screenshots of disapprovals or suspensions<br />
- Landing page URLs and screenshots for corresponding ads<br />
- Business license and legal representative ID (if applicable)<br />
- Product certification and trademark registration certificates</p>
<p><strong>Drafting Appeal Statement</strong>:<br />
The appeal email needs to include the following elements:<br />
1. Brief problem description: Account ID, issue type, occurrence time<br />
2. Root cause analysis: Sincerely acknowledge possible issues<br />
3. Rectification measures: Specifically describe taken or upcoming improvement measures<br />
4. Commitment guarantee: Express determination for compliant operations</p>
<h3>3.2 Appeal Channels for Different Scenarios</h3>
<p><strong>Scenario 1: Ad Disapproval</strong></p>
<p>If individual ads are disapproved, first use the ad preview tool to view specific violation reasons, then:<br />
1. Modify ad content to ensure policy compliance<br />
2. Click "Request Review" in the ad editing page<br />
3. Usually receive review results within 1-2 business days</p>
<p><strong>Scenario 2: Account Suspension</strong></p>
<p>Account-level suspension is a serious situation requiring:<br />
1. Visit the Google Ads policy support page<br />
2. Select "Account Suspended" option<br />
3. Fill in detailed problem description and appeal reasons<br />
4. Submit business license and other qualification documents</p>
<p><strong>Scenario 3: Domain Blacklisted</strong></p>
<p>If the entire domain is marked as a malicious website by Google:<br />
1. First check for website security issues in Google Search Console<br />
2. Fix all security issues (malware, phishing pages, etc.)<br />
3. Apply for website security re-review<br />
4. After approval, submit ad appeal</p>
<h3>3.3 Appeal Email Template</h3>
<pre><code>Subject: Appeal Request - Google Ads Account #[Your Account ID]

Dear Google Ads Policy Team,

I am writing to request a review of our suspended Google Ads account.

Account Details:
- Customer ID: [Your Customer ID]
- Website URL: [Your Website]
- Suspension Date: [Date]

Issue Description:
We recently received notification that our account was suspended due to [specific reason]. After thorough internal review, we understand that [briefly explain the issue].

Corrective Actions Taken:
1. [Specific action 1, e.g., Removed misleading claims from ad copy]
2. [Specific action 2, e.g., Updated landing page to match ad promises]
3. [Specific action 3, e.g., Obtained necessary certifications]

We have always been committed to compliance with Google Ads policies and have implemented stricter internal review processes to prevent similar issues in the future.

Attached are the relevant documents supporting our appeal:
- Business License
- Product Certifications
- Updated Ad Copy and Landing Pages

We kindly request your reconsideration of our account status. Thank you for your time and consideration.

Best regards,
[Your Name]
[Company Name]
[Contact Information]
</code></pre>
<h3>3.4 Appeal Progress Tracking</h3>
<p><strong>Normal Appeal Cycles</strong>:<br />
- Ad-level appeal: 1-3 business days<br />
- Account-level appeal: 3-7 business days<br />
- Domain security issue appeal: 7-14 business days</p>
<p><strong>Follow-up Suggestions</strong>:<br />
1. Wait at least 5 business days after the first appeal before following up<br />
2. Follow up through official Twitter @GoogleAds or Google Business Profile<br />
3. If no response within 30 days, submit a second appeal with new evidence materials</p>
<hr />
<h2>Part 4: 2024 Policy Updates and Response Suggestions</h2>
<h3>4.1 Key Policy Updates</h3>
<p><strong>User-Generated Content (UGC) Platform Restrictions</strong>: Starting from 2024, Google has strengthened advertising restrictions on UGC platforms (such as forums and comment sections), requiring additional verification.</p>
<p><strong>AI-Generated Content Labeling Requirements</strong>: If websites use a large amount of AI-generated content, clear labeling is required; otherwise, they may be judged as "low-quality content."</p>
<p><strong>Privacy Compliance Upgrade</strong>: With stronger enforcement of regulations like GDPR and CCPA, cookie usage and user data collection require greater transparency.</p>
<h3>4.2 Long-term Compliance Operation Suggestions</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Establish Internal Review Mechanism</strong>: Set up at least two-level review processes before ads go live</li>
<li><strong>Regular Policy Learning</strong>: Check Google Ads policy update logs monthly</li>
<li><strong>Preserve Operation Logs</strong>: Recommend retaining all ad modification records for at least 6 months</li>
<li><strong>Diversify Risks</strong>: For larger budgets, configure multiple accounts for risk diversification</li>
</ol>
